The simple value of this attribute stands for an identifier of this data object within the system, it can be used as a reference from other objects within the same system (i.e. primary and foreign keys), and it should be unique per type of object. The same data object copied to a different system will likely have a different "id" in the new system since "id" values are system specific and do not represent persistent business identifiers. Business identifiers are assigned outside the information system and are captured in the "identifier" field. The "id" field is more likely to be a serially or randomly generated value that is assigned to the data object as it is created in a system.

identifier.description: A 'business' identifier or accession number for the entity, typically as provided by an external system or authority, that are globally unique and persist across implementing systems. Also, since these identifiers are created outside the information system through a specific business process, the Identifier type has additional attributes to capture this additional metadata so the actual identifier values are qualified by the context that created those values. This additional context allows "identifier" instances to be transmitted as business data across systems while still being able to trace them back to the system of origin.

number_of_cycles.description: The number of treatment cycles the subject received.

regimen.description: The regimen or line of therapy

subject.description: The subject (person, animal, model system) to which the treatment was administered.

therapeutic_agent.description: One or more therapeutic agents that are administered as part of this treatment.

treatment_anatomic_site.description: The anatomical site that the treatment targets.

treatment_effect.description: The effect of a treatment on the diagnosis or tumor.

treatment_for_diagnosis.description: The diagnosis for which this treatment is intended.

treatment_frequency.description: The frequency of using the substance described by this instance.

treatment_intent.description: The medical intent of the treatment.

treatment_outcome.description: The final outcome of the treatment.

treatment_type.description: The type of treatment administered, which may include medication/therapeutics or other procedures.
